    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-09-03T18:43:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-09-03T18:43:00-05:00" n="374"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d374">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">796.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss>/9–354:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 374<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Philippines</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-09-03T19:43:00-04:00"
                            >September 3, 1954—7:43 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>883. Department and Defense considering Philippines request purchase reimbursable
                    basis 400 pounds napalm thickener. Before approving Department wishes know (1)
                    whether State-Defense agreement use napalm contained Army telegram to <gloss
                        target="#t_JUSMAGPHIL1">JUSMAGPHIL</gloss> DA 90243 December 21 [<hi
                        rend="italic">18</hi>], 1951<note n="1" xml:id="d374fn1">For text, see <ref
                            target="frus1951v06p2#pg_1593">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1951, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">vi</hi>, Part 2, p. 1593</ref>.</note> still
                    believed effective and necessary and (2) whether Embassy and <gloss
                        target="#t_JUSMAG1">JUSMAG</gloss> perceive objection filling present
                        request.<note n="2" xml:id="d374fn2">
                        <p>The Embassy in Manila sent the following reply on Sept. 29:</p>
                        <p>“Department 883, Napalm.</p>
                        <p>“(1) Embassy and <gloss target="#t_JUSMAG1">JUSMAG</gloss> believe cited
                            agreement use napalm effective and necessary.</p>
                        <p>“(2) Both Embassy and <gloss target="#t_JUSMAG1">JUSMAG</gloss> foresee
                            complications from control standpoint if napalm purchased on
                            reimbursable basis.</p>
                        <p>“According Embassy files existing agreement applicable napalm furnished
                            non-reimbursable basis. <gloss target="#t_JUSMAG1">JUSMAG</gloss>
                            desires retain control use napalm in accordance with existing
                            agreement.” (Telegram 970; 796.5 <gloss target="#t_MSP1"
                            >MSP</gloss>/9–2954)</p>
                        <p>A notation on the file copy of telegram 970 by James Bell, Officer in
                            Charge of Philippine Affairs, reads: “S/<gloss target="#t_MSA1"
                                >MSA</gloss> to refuse Phil request”.</p>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
